and she is delivered by the standard of cesarean section. The placenta is
transfered to the neonatal intensive care unit, and intravenous thiopental
is administered prior to the neonate's transfer. No resuscitation
interventions were necessary due to intrauterine death and anuria.
Following birth, the neonate was evaluated for cardiac abnormalities,
and her blood chemistries were monitored. The neonate's blood culture
cultures were positive for P. aeruginosa. At 6:30am, the neonate was
placed on mechanical ventilator. At 7:30am the mother was placed
on continuous renal replacement. The neonate was transferred to the
newborn intensive care unit at 7:30am. The neonate remains stable
on mechanical ventilator, receiving neonatal therapeutics. She continues
to breathe spontaneously and is responsive to the neonatal care team.

A 101 NP was summoned for examination, infant was examined and found to have a fever of 102.3F.

Baby was taken to the NICU.
Cultures were obtained including urine and blood. No growth restriction was found.
Infant was given Glucolytic supplements and administered with an infusion of Gamma Glutamyl Tyrosine.
Mother was given a dose of Acetaminophen 250 mg.
Disseminated/invasive infection was presumed.

ADMINISTRATION: The primary method of coronary artery bypass grafting is to perform a graft from the left ventricle to the left anterior descending artery with the goal being to cross to the right anterior descending (RAD) artery which carries the flow of blood into the anterior descending artery to the myocardium.
On this date, the first procedure was to the RAD artery; the RAD artery was identified by placement of a small endoprosthesis in the tricuspid groove and it went straight into the RAD.
To confirm the position of the graft, an x-ray was performed. The x-ray showed a graft in the RAD artery and the graft was delivered at the anastomotic site.
The patient was then placed on an ECMO, in the operating room, to place the graft. 
The procedure was completed successfully and a follow-up CT scan (at 24 hours) showed no evidence of leakage.

referral system is available to other units in the hospital for
questions regarding patients that are seen by this service.
